{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4ded0856-c724-4d08-b88a-53e45dd634f7","content":"On macOS, the OS automatically captures crash reports — no `createdump` needed:\n\n**Crash reports are saved to:**\n- `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (user-launched apps)\n- `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (system-wide)\n\nLook for `.ips` or `.crash` files matching your process name and timestamp.\n\n**Quick way to find them:**\n```bash\nls -lt ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/ | head\n```\n\n**Core dumps** (if you also want a full memory dump):\n1. Run `ulimit -c unlimited` before launching your app.\n2. After crash, look in `/cores/` for `core.<pid>`.\n\n> Note: SIP (System Integrity Protection) may block core dump generation. The `.ips` crash report is usually sufficient and always available — it includes the faulting thread's backtrace, register state, and loaded images.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"edaa1e3f-7e72-4bac-afd3-396df44f5cd7","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app that crashed on macOS, specifically without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — I don't need to search the codebase for this.\n\nOn macOS, when an app crashes, the system automatically generates crash reports. Let me provide the key locations and tips.","outputTokens":322,"requestId":"7645:30B4C0:E26CBD:1095816:69FE9215"},"id":"6dbc61d4-4a09-44ee-aba6-29e383bc6ebf","timestamp":"2026-05-09T01:47:11.723Z","parentId":"08b29739-9e74-418c-afd3-8e144c078c82"}
